# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-legal-defense-fund
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] A **501(c)(3) organization** is a United States corporation, trust, unincorporated association, or other type of organization exempt from federal income tax under section 501(c)(3) of Title 26 of the United States Code.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] It is one of the 29 types of 501(c) nonprofit organizations in the U.S.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] The 501(c)(3) exemption applies also for any non-incorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association or foundation organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as *Friends of* organizations.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] 26 U.S.C. § 170 provides a deduction for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Regulations specify which such deductions must be verifiable to be allowed (e.g., receipts for donations of $250 or more).
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] The basic requirement of obtaining tax-exempt status is that the organization is specifically limited in powers to purposes that the IRS classifies as tax-exempt purposes.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] This limiting of the powers is crucial to obtaining tax exempt status with the IRS and then on the state level.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Organizations acquire 501(c)(3) tax exemption by filing IRS Form 1023.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] As of 2006, the form must be accompanied by an $850 filing fee if the yearly gross receipts for the organization are expected to average $10,000 or more.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] If yearly gross receipts are expected to average less than $10,000, the filing fee is reduced to $400.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] The IRS released a software tool called Cyber Assistant in 2013, which was succeeded by Form 1023-EZ in 2014.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] There is an alternative way for an organization to obtain status if an organization has applied for a determination and either there is an actual controversy regarding a determination or the Internal Revenue Service has failed to make a determination.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Prior to December 30, 1969, nonprofit organizations could declare themselves to be tax-exempt under Section 501(c)(3) without first obtaining Internal Revenue Service recognition by filing Form 1023 and receiving a determination letter.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] A nonprofit organization that did so prior to that date could still be subject to challenge of its status by the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] An individual may not take a tax deduction on gifts made to a 501(c)(3) organization that is organized and operated exclusively for the testing for public safety.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] In the case of tuition fees paid to a private 501(c)(3) school or a church school, the payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions because they are payments for services rendered to the payee or the payee's children.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] The payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions even if a significant portion of a church school's curriculum is religious education.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] For a payment to be a tax-deductible charitable contribution, it must be a voluntary transfer of money or other property with no expectation of procuring financial benefit equal to the transfer amount.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Before donating to a 501(c)(3) organization, a donor can consult the searchable online IRS list of charitable organizations to verify that the organization qualifies to receive tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Consumers may file IRS Form 13909, with documentation, to complain about inappropriate or fraudulent (i.e., fundraising, political campaigning, lobbying) activities by any 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Most 501(c)(3) must disclose the names and addresses of certain large donors to the Internal Revenue Service on their annual returns, but this information is not required to be made available to the public, unless the organization is an independent foundation.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Churches are generally exempt from this reporting requirement.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Every 501(c)(3) organization must make available for public inspection its application for tax-exemption, including its Form 1023 or Form 1023-EZ and any attachments, supporting documents, and follow-up correspondence with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Annual returns must be publicly available for a three-year period beginning with the due date of the return, including any extension of time for filing.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] The Internal Revenue Service provides information about specific 501(c)(3) organizations through its Tax Exempt Organization Search online.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] A private nonprofit organization, GuideStar, provides information on 501(c)(3) organizations.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] ProPublica's Nonprofit Explorer provides copies of each organization's Form 990 and, for some organizations, audited financial statements.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] WikiCharities, is a nonprofit database of nonprofits and charities by name, location, and topic, that allows each organization to report its financials, leadership, contacts, and other activities.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] However, Open990 was a searchable database of information about organizations that had to shut down due to IRS delays in posting information online.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are prohibited from supporting political candidates, as a result of the Johnson Amendment enacted in 1954.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are subject to limits on lobbying, having a choice between two sets of rules establishing an upper bound for their lobbying activities.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Section 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of their tax-exempt status if these rules are violated.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] An organization that loses its 501(c)(3) status due to being engaged in political activities cannot subsequently qualify for 501(c)(3) status.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] As a result, it is common for 501(c)(3) organizations to have affiliated nonprofits that are classified as 501(c)(4) organizations, allowing the affiliate to engage in political activity without threatening 501(c)(3) status.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Churches must meet specific requirements to obtain and maintain tax-exempt status; these are outlined in "IRS Publication 1828: Tax Guide for Churches and Religious Organizations".
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] This guide outlines activities allowed and not allowed by churches under the 501(c)(3) designation.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Schools for the preparation of its ministers.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Having an established congregation served by an organized ministry is of central importance.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Points 4, 6, 8, 11, 12, and 13 are also especially important.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Nevertheless, the 14-point list is a guideline; it is not intended to be all-encompassing, and other facts and circumstances may be relevant factors.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Although there is no definitive definition of a church for Internal Revenue Code purposes, in 1986 the United States Tax Court said that "A church is a coherent group of individuals and families that join together to accomplish the religious purposes of mutually held beliefs.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] The United States Tax Court has stated that, while a church can certainly broadcast its religious services by radio, radio broadcasts themselves do not constitute a congregation unless there is a group of people physically attending those religious services.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] A church can conduct worship services in various specific locations rather than in one official location.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] A church may have a significant number of people associate themselves with the church on a regular basis, even if the church does not have a traditional established list of individual members.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] In order to qualify as a tax-exempt church, church activities must be a significant part of the organization's operations.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] An organization whose operations include a substantial nonexempt commercial purposes, such as operating restaurants and grocery stores in a manner consistent with a particular religion's religious beliefs does not qualify as a tax-exempt church.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] In practice, hospital policies often don't cover outside contracted physicians or narrowly defined medically necessary services, leaving patients who technically qualify for charity care still responsible for significant medical bills.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Since section 501(c)(3)'s political-activity prohibition was enacted, "commentators and litigants have challenged the provision on numerous constitutional grounds", such as freedom of speech, vagueness, and equal protection and selective prosecution.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Historically, Supreme Court decisions, such as *Regan v.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Taxation with Representation of Washington*, suggested that the Court, if it were to squarely examine the political-activity prohibition of § 501(c)(3), would uphold it against a constitutional challenge.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] However, some have suggested that a successful challenge to the political activities prohibition of Section 501(c)(3) might be more plausible in light of *Citizens United v.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] In contrast to the prohibition on political campaign interventions by all section 501(c)(3) organizations, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Although the law states that "no substantial part" of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities with large budgets may lawfully expend a million dollars (under the "expenditure" test) or more (under the "substantial part" test) per year on lobbying.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] The Internal Revenue Service has never defined the term "substantial part" with respect to lobbying.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] To establish a safe harbor for the "substantial part" test, the United States Congress enacted §501(h), called the Conable election after its author, Representative Barber Conable.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] The section establishes limits based on operating budget that a charity can use to determine if it meets the substantial test.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] This changes the prohibition against direct intervention in partisan contests only for lobbying.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] The organization is now presumed in compliance with the substantiality test if they work within the limits.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] The Conable election requires a charity to file a declaration with the IRS and file a functional distribution of funds spreadsheet with their Form 990.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] IRS form 5768 is required to make the Conable election.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to award grants to foreign charitable organizations if the grants are intended for charitable purposes and the grant funds are subject to the 501(c)(3) organization's control.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Additional procedures are required of 501(c)(3) organizations that are private foundations.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] The 501(c)(3) organization's management should review the grant application from the foreign organization, decide whether to award the grant based on the intended use of the funds, and require continuous oversight based on the use of funds.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] If the donor imposes a restriction or earmark that the contribution must be used for foreign activities, then the contribution is deemed to be for the foreign organization rather than the 501(c)(3) organization, and the contribution is not tax-deductible.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] The purpose of the grant to the foreign organization cannot include endorsing or opposing political candidates for elected office in any country.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/501-c-3] If a 501(c)(3) organization sets up and controls a foreign subsidiary to facilitate charitable work in a foreign country, then donors' contributions to the 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible even if intended to fund the foreign charitable activities.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The **Animal Legal Defense Fund** is an American animal law advocacy organization.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Its stated mission is to protect the lives and advance the interests of animals through the legal system.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In addition to their national headquarters in Cotati, California, the Animal Legal Defense Fund maintains an office in Portland, Oregon.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund goes to court for animals.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] From filing high-impact lawsuits to providing *amicus curiae* briefs, its litigation work is a primary tool in the work to advance the interests of animals.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund's team of expert staff attorneys may bring suit themselves, or it may retain outside counsel for representation.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Its civil actions on behalf of animals often include filing *amicus curiae* briefs arguing the case for recognition of the bonds between humans and nonhuman animals and filing formal complaints against government agencies charged with enforcing laws meant to protect animals.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund's Criminal Justice Program is staffed by attorneys, including former prosecutors, with expertise in animal protection law who provide free legal assistance to prosecutors, law enforcement, and veterinarians handling animal cruelty cases.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] It also works with state legislators to strengthen criminal animal protection laws.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund's Animal Law Program works closely with law students and law professionals to advance the emerging field of animal law.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Working to expand the practice and understanding of animal law in the legal community, the Animal Legal Defense Fund partners with attorneys and pro bono coordinators across the country.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The program utilizes these volunteers to support the Animal Legal Defense Fund's litigation, criminal justice, and legislative goals.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund works at the state and local levels to advance important legislation.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Legislative Affairs Program advocates for laws that promote or protect the lives and interests of animals and opposes legislation that would be detrimental to animals’ well-being.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund's annual report comprehensively surveys animal protection laws of all U.S. states and territories.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] It is the longest-running and most authoritative report of its kind, assessing the strength of each jurisdiction's animal protection laws by examining over 4,000 pages of statutes.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The report also highlights the top, middle and bottom tiers of jurisdictions and notes the "Best Five" and "Worst Five" states overall.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In December, the Supreme Court denied the foie gras industry's petition challenging California's ban on the sale of foie gras.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals' mandate went into immediate effect, banning foie gras in California.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund filed numerous amicus briefs in the six-plus years of litigation, urging courts to uphold the law.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In October, the Animal Legal Defense Fund and the National Council of Juvenile and Family Court Judges (NCJFCJ) announced a first-of-its-kind partnership to address judicial response in court cases related to animal cruelty.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In March 2018, a consumer protection lawsuit was filed by the Animal Legal Defense Fund against Trader Joe's on behalf of an egg purchaser.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The lawsuit sought to stop Trader Joe's from deceptively and misleadingly labeling its cage-free eggs.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The consumer argued that Trader Joe's was violating multiple California consumer protection laws by selling cage-free eggs in cartons with representations of hens foraging in pastures, when the eggs were actually from industrial hen houses, where hens do not have access to the outdoors.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The case reached a settlement in June 2018, in which Trader Joe's agreed to pull the packaging not only in California but nationwide.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In the spring of 2018, after the Animal Legal Defense Fund announced its intent to sue Deer Haven Mini Zoo in Keymar, Maryland for violations of the federal Endangered Species Act and state cruelty laws, the owners agreed to voluntarily relinquish some of the animals on the property.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Two endangered lemurs, a bobcat, six arctic foxes, four cavies, and a coatimundi were removed from the unaccredited roadside menagerie and transferred to sanctuaries.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In August, a California judge ordered Manning Beef, a slaughterhouse, to pay $94,500 in attorneys' fees after Manning falsely accused Los Angeles Cow Save, a group that organized vigils for animals killed at the slaughterhouse, of trespassing.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The fees were awarded after the Animal Legal Defense Fund, the Law Offices of Matthew Strugar, and attorney Ryan Gordon filed an anti-SLAPP motion on behalf of the group.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] District Court of Utah ruled the Utah ag-gag statute was unconstitutional, the second decision against an ag-gag statute affirming it was unconstitutional.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Both rulings were due to lawsuits filed by the Animal Legal Defense Fund.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Ag-gag laws criminalize undercover investigations at factory farms and slaughterhouses that often expose serious animal cruelty and violations of environmental and safety laws.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In February, the inhumane King Kong Zoological Park in North Carolina shut down permanently after the Animal Legal Defense Fund filed a lawsuit alleging the zoo's treatment of animals violated North Carolina's animal cruelty laws.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] North Carolina's unique civil animal cruelty law empowers concerned members of the public to report when criminal animal cruelty laws go ignored and under-enforced, as they did at the King Kong Zoo.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In September, the Animal Legal Defense Fund won a lawsuit against the Pennsylvania Deptartment of Agriculture for dogs suffering in puppy mills.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The department was forced to reinstate comprehensive regulations for commercial dog breeders.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The rules had prohibited some of the cruelest and most inhumane practices, such as keeping mother dogs in cages with metal wirestrand flooring and never letting mother dogs outside for exercise.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In August, the Animaland Zoological Park in Pennsylvania permanently shut down in response to a March 2016 lawsuit filed by the Animal Legal Defense Fund.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The lawsuit alleged that the zoo violated the Endangered Species Act and state wildlife laws by failing to provide adequate care for animals confined at the facility.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Two bears and an endangered wolf were relocated to sanctuaries that are capable of meeting their needs.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In February, the Animal Legal Defense Fund won an Endangered Species Act lawsuit on behalf of four tigers and three lemurs held in substandard captivity at Cricket Hollow Zoo, a roadside zoo in Iowa.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] This victory is the first time that animal advocates successfully used the Endangered Species Act to obtain a court order for the removal of captive animals from substandard conditions, and sets important precedent that isolation of social animals violates the Act.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In October, the California Coastal Commission voted at the Animal Legal Defense Fund's request that SeaWorld San Diego must discontinue its captive orca breeding program in order to proceed with its Blue World expansion plans at that facility.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In February, the Animal Legal Defense Fund settled its public nuisance lawsuit against Jim Mack's Ice Cream to secure the release of a female black bear named Ricki from her 16-year confinement at the ice cream shop to the Colorado-based Wild Animal Sanctuary.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] District Court for the District of Idaho ruled that the state's ag-gag law, Idaho Code sec.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] 18-7042, violates the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the U.S.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Constitution, the first time a court had declared an ag-gag statute unconstitutional and a landmark victory for a broad-based public interest coalition of national nonprofits, including the Animal Legal Defense Fund, PETA, the ACLU of Idaho, and the Center for Food Safety.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund and PETA believe that the current confinement conditions are prohibited by the ESA.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] This may lead to Lolita being retired from performing and transferred to a seaside sanctuary.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In January 2014, Caltrans agreed to remove bird-killing nets at a local highway project, and vowed to use safer construction methods, after settling with the Animal Legal Defense Fund and conservation groups.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In July 2013, the Animal Legal Defense Fund filed the first lawsuit in the nation to challenge the constitutionality of an ag-gag law.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Utah's law, which criminalizes the videotaping on factory farms, attacks activity protected under the U.S.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Constitution's First and Fourteenth Amendments.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Also in July 2013, eleven bears were removed from gladiator-style bear pits at a North Carolina roadside zoo after the Animal Legal Defense Fund sent the Chief Saunooke Bear Park a letter threatening to sue for ongoing harm to the grizzlies.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In March, the Clay County (Kentucky) Circuit Court entered an agreed order of judgment resolving the Animal Legal Defense Fund's lawsuit against the county to stop systematic abuses at the local animal shelter.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Following the lawsuit, which was based on an undercover video, Cal-Cruz is no longer in operation, and the former owner may no longer work with animals.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In August, a North Carolina judge granted Ben the Bear permanent sanctuary at the Performing Animal Welfare Society as a result of a lawsuit against Jambbas Ranch—Animal Legal Defense Fund attorneys worked to represent the plaintiffs.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Ben had languished for years on cement in a chain-link kennel—he now has the chance to live like a bear should, with plenty of space to roam, play, and forage in his new habitat.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In February, Guam voted to dramatically strengthen the territory's laws protecting animals.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Guam's new legislation adopts robust minimum care standards and other definitions which mirror much of what is contained in the Animal Legal Defense Fund's model animal protection laws.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In November, the Animal Legal Defense Fund won its lawsuit to free Tony the Tiger from the Tiger Truck Stop in Grosse Tete, Louisiana.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The judge ordered the Louisiana Department of Wildlife and Fisheries to revoke the current permit and prohibited it from issuing any new permits to the Truck Stop.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Kenneth Lang Jr. pleaded guilty to animal cruelty in January 2010.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund secured permanent custody of seven horses rescued from Michael, Judy, and Gayle Keating, the abusive North Carolina owners who allowed them to starve nearly to death, in the case of ALDF v.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] On October 6, the United States Supreme Court directly addressed the issue of animal cruelty for the first time in more than fifteen years.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund submitted an amicus curiae brief in the case of U.S. v.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] Stevens, urging the Court to uphold the law and recognize that the prevention of cruelty to animals is a compelling government interest.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In August, the Animal Legal Defense Fund filed lawsuits in Kentucky against Estill and Robertson Counties for neglecting their homeless animals, despite their legal requirement to provide basic humane care.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund called on Kentucky's legislature to push for comprehensive changes in its laws protecting horses and other animals.
[src:animal-legal-defense-fund/animal-legal-defense-fund] In 2008, Kentucky ranked last in the nation for animal protection laws.
